    <!-- Curatorial Thesis Summary -->
    <section id="statement-summary" class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-zinc-900 border-b border-gray-700">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold protest-red mb-8 uppercase tracking-wider">The Exhibition's Thesis</h2>
            <div class="max-w-4xl text-lg space-y-6 text-gray-200">
                <p>
                    <strong class="protest-red">This exhibition argues that contemporary art does not simply reflect the world's political and social climate. Instead, it influences and molds it.</strong> Art is positioned in an engaged, essential role in national dialogue, where criticism is sounded, injustices are confronted, and alternative futures are imagined. By tackling issues like climate change, migration, gender and racial justice, and the precariousness of democracy, these artists show that creativity is not peripheral to politics. It is a driving force.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Moving beyond aesthetic critique, the artists here destabilize institutions of power, subvert dominant narratives, and give voice to marginalized communities. Their work functions as both critique and catalyst, reordering what is seen, said, and felt within a society—a vital **reconsideration of what democracy feels like and whom it serves.**
                </p>
                <a href="#full-statement" class="inline-block mt-4 text-white hover:text-[#ff3859] border-b-2 border-transparent hover:border-[#ff3859] transition-all">Read Full Statement →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Featured Artworks Section - Now includes 10 individual artworks -->
    <section id="artworks" class="py-16 md:py-24">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-black text-white mb-12">Featured Interventions (10 Artworks)</h2>

            <!-- Artwork Grid (Responsive: 1 col, 2 cols, 3 cols) -->
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 xl:grid-cols-4 gap-8">

                <!-- 1. Agnes Denes: Wheatfield -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Denes%3A+Wheatfield+1982" alt="Image of Agnes Denes's Wheatfield - A Confrontation." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Agnes Denes</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Wheatfield – A Confrontation (1982)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        Her colossal land art intervention—seeding two acres of wheat into a landfill bordering the World Trade Center—was a lyrical but caustic commentary on wasted economic resources during times of financial turmoil.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 2. Hank Willis Thomas: All Power to All People -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Thomas%3A+All+Power+2017" alt="Image of Hank Willis Thomas's massive afro pick sculpture." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Hank Willis Thomas</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">All Power to All People (2017)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        Set near a monument to white supremacy, the massive afro pick, topped with a Black Power fist, is both a celebration of cultural identity and a visual act of reclaiming public space as a space of resistance.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 3. Nicole Eisenman: Morning Affirmations -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Eisenman%3A+Affirmations+2018" alt="Image of Nicole Eisenman's Morning Affirmations." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Nicole Eisenman</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Morning Affirmations (2018)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        A caustic satire piece whereby a Bald Eagle, the national symbol, stands gazing at itself in the mirror, bearing an unimitative resemblance to a contemporary political leader.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 4. Nicole Eisenman: The Triumph of Poverty -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Eisenman%3A+Triumph+of+Poverty+2009" alt="Image of Nicole Eisenman's The Triumph of Poverty." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Nicole Eisenman</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">The Triumph of Poverty (2009)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        Imagined in the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis, this painting presents a stark vision of zombie-like people lost in despair, standing for the dehumanizing conditions of economic collapse.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 5. Banksy: I Love New York; Don't We All? -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Banksy%3A+I+Love+NY+2008" alt="Image of Banksy's 'I Love New York; Don't We All?' graffiti piece." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Banksy</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">I Love New York; Don't We All? (2008)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        This mural, featuring an engorged rat wearing an "I Heart NY" t-shirt, mocks the commercialization of civic pride and tourism and highlights how American cultural malaise has world implications.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 6. Banksy: Fuck the Police -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Banksy%3A+F*ck+the+Police+2000" alt="Image of Banksy's 'Fuck the Police' graffiti piece." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Banksy</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Fuck the Police (2000)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        Attacks the epidemic of police brutality across the U.S. and ties it to worldwide movements against state violence, reinforcing the transnational nature of political opposition.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 7. Nicole Eisenman: Hanging Birth -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Eisenman%3A+Hanging+Birth+1994" alt="Image of Nicole Eisenman's Hanging Birth." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Nicole Eisenman</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Hanging Birth (1994)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        The gruesome imagery of the forced birth of a woman represents the ongoing struggle over reproductive rights in the U.S., anticipating the erosion of bodily autonomy by state power.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 8. Nicole Eisenman: Tea Party -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Eisenman%3A+Tea+Party+2011" alt="Image of Nicole Eisenman's Tea Party painting." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Nicole Eisenman</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Tea Party (2011)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        A satirical commentary revealing the crossing of politics, religion, and corporate interests, exposing the hypocrisy of American conservatism and the theatrics of populist sentiment.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 9. The Secret Handshake: Statue of Trump and Epstein Holding Hands -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Secret+Handshake%3A+Trump+%26+Epstein+2025" alt="Image of The Secret Handshake's Statue of Trump and Epstein Holding Hands." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">The Secret Handshake</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Statue of Trump and Epstein Holding Hands (2025)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        This sculpture represents public outrage towards institutional impunity by mirroring the grotesque intersection of political and economic elites whose misdeeds often go unchallenged.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- 10. Daniel J. Martinez: Museum Tags -->
                <div class="p-6 bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl hover:shadow-2xl transition-shadow">
                    <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/000000/FFFFFF?text=Martinez%3A+Museum+Tags+1993" alt="Image of Daniel J. Martinez's Museum Tags installation." class="w-full h-40 object-cover rounded-lg mb-4 border-2 border-[#ff3859]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold protest-red">Daniel J. Martinez</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg font-light mb-3 italic">Museum Tags (1993)</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">
                        The famous museum intervention where tags read, "I can't imagine ever wanting to be white," transforming the institutional space itself into a politicized, contentious site.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Full Curatorial Statement Section -->
    <section id="full-statement" class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-gray-900 border-t-4 border-[#ff3859]">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h2 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-black protest-red mb-12">The Full Statement</h2>

            <div class="max-w-4xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300">
                <!-- Paragraph 1 -->
                <p>
                    Contemporary Art in the Modern Political Landscape and Its Influence is not only an exhibition, but a statement of intent. It argues that contemporary art does not simply reflect the world's political and social climate. Instead, it influences and molds it. In so doing, art becomes an activator of change and a force against institutional corruption. The show demolishes the mythology of art as a passive observer of culture and history. It positions art in an engaged, essential role in national dialogue. Here, criticism is sounded, injustices are confronted, and alternative futures are imagined. Through diverse artworks addressing systemic racism, environmental destruction, gender discrimination, and the abuse of power, this exhibition argues that art is one of the strongest languages of protest and transformation in society.
                </p>
                <!-- Paragraph 2 -->
                <p>
                    The exhibition's argument depends on the belief that art can reflect and define the political consciousness of its time. Today's artists, the show insists, are not content to merely represent or document social crises. Rather, they destabilize institutions of power, subvert dominant narratives, and give voice to marginalized communities. By tackling issues like climate change, migration, gender and racial justice, and the precariousness of American democracy, these artists show that creativity is not peripheral to politics. It is a driving force. Their practice recalls how aesthetic space structures collective imagination, mobilizes empathy, and catalyzes civic action.
                </p>
                <!-- Paragraph 3 (Political Discourse) -->
                <p>
                    The political discourse in the United States today is marked by extreme polarization, widespread corruption, and pervasive distrust of democratic institutions. It requires an equally robust cultural and artistic response. The artists in this exhibition fill that need. They move beyond aesthetic critique to engage in public debate. Their work does not merely reflect reality—it remakes it. They show us how art functions as both critique and catalyst, fostering an interdependent exchange between political power and creative expression. Political events frame artistic creation, but art can frame public perception and even influence policy. This active interaction recalls theorist Jacques Rancière's notion of the "distribution of the sensible."
                </p>
                <!-- Paragraph 4 (Conclusion/Call to Action) -->
                <p>
                    <strong class="protest-red">Finally, the show works as an act of provocation.</strong> It seeks not just to present art, but to energize onlookers. Its central argument is that contemporary art can read, comment on, and invert current political and social issues, and act as a major force for change. This idea is reflected in the work of cultural critic bell hooks, who felt that art could be a "space of radical possibility." Through making art that is oppositional to domination and proactive in defending human dignity, current artists offer visions of freedom that are not limited to the museum space. The show is then no longer a reflection of political reality, but an act of political imagination—a space where the public can envision more equitable futures.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Footer -->
